tart=100)\n  * [4 ](/search/?query=finetuning+large+language+models&searchtype=all&source=header&start=150)\n  * [5 ](/search/?query=finetuning+large+language+models&searchtype=all&source=header&start=200)\n  * …\n\n\n\n  1. [arXiv:2603.22799](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.22799)  [[pdf](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.22799), [ps](https://arxiv.org/ps/2603.22799), [other](https://arxiv.org/format/2603.22799)] \n\ncs.CL\n\nSpan Modeling for Idiomaticity and Figurative Language Detection with Span Contrastive Loss \n\nAuthors: [Blake Matheny](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Matheny%2C+B), [Phuong Minh Nguyen](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Nguyen%2C+P+M), [Minh Le Nguyen](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Nguyen%2C+M+L)\n\nAbstract:  The category of figurative language contains many varieties, some of which are non-compositional in nature. This type of phrase or multi-word expression (MWE) includes idioms, which represent a single meaning that does not consist of the sum of its words. For… ▽ More The category of figurative language contains many varieties, some of which are non-compositional in nature. This type of phrase or multi-word expression (MWE) includes idioms, which represent a single meaning that does not consist of the sum of its words. For language models, this presents a unique problem due to tokenization and adjacent contextual embeddings. Many large language models have overcome this issue with large phrase vocabulary, though immediate recognition frequently fails without one- or few-shot prompting or instruction finetuning. The best results have been achieved with BERT-based or LSTM finetuning approaches. The model in this paper contains one such variety. We propose BERT- and RoBERTa-based models finetuned with a combination of slot loss and span contrastive loss (SCL) with hard negative reweighting to improve idiomaticity detection, attaining state of the art sequence accuracy performance on existing datasets. Comparative ablation studies show the effectiveness of SCL and its generalizability. The geometric mean of F1 and sequence accuracy (SA) is also proposed to assess a model's span awareness and general performance together. △ Less\n\nSubmitted 24 March, 2026; originally announced March 2026. \n\n  2. [arXiv:2603.20957](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.20957)  [[pdf](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.20957), [ps](https://arxiv.org/ps/2603.20957), [other](https://arxiv.org/format/2603.20957)] \n\ncs.CL cs.AI cs.CY\n\nAlignment Whack-a-Mole : Finetuning Activates Verbatim Recall of Copyrighted Books in Large Language Models\n\nAuthors: [Xinyue Liu](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Liu%2C+X), [Niloofar Mireshghallah](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Mireshghallah%2C+N), [Jane C. Ginsburg](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Ginsburg%2C+J+C), [Tuhin Chakrabarty](/search/?searchtype=author&query=Chakrabarty%2C+T)\n\nAbstract:  Frontier LLM companies have repeatedly assured courts and regulators that their models do not store copies of training data. They further rely on safety alignment strategies via RLHF, system prompts, and output filters to \n...[内容已截断]"
